    - ["mp3316023",  operator.contains, [multiprocessing.managers._BaseDictProxy.__dict__, "__irshift__"], false]
    - ["mp3316024",  operator.contains, [multiprocessing.managers._BaseSetProxy.__dict__,  "__irshift__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __ipow__, __ilshift__, __irshift__ across all 8 mp subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 8 classes x 3 methods = 24 rows.
# __ipow__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# __ilshift__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# __irshift__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# All 24 values are false.
# Wave 660 already established that the forward operators __pow__, __lshift__,
#   and __rshift__ are all false for all 8 mp types. The in-place variants
#   tested here follow directly: absent forward operator implies absent
#   in-place variant.
# BaseListProxy note — no asymmetry in this wave (contrast with wave 666):
#   Unlike wave 666 where BaseListProxy.__iadd__ and __imul__ were false despite
#   __add__ and __mul__ being true (wave 658), this wave has no such asymmetry.
#   Wave 660 already found __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ all false for
#   BaseListProxy (list defines none of these). The in-place variants are
#   therefore absent from BaseListProxy for the same underlying reason.
# _BaseSetProxy note: set defines __and__, __or__, __xor__, __sub__ for set
#   algebra (wave 661 found __and__/__or__/__xor__ false for the proxy), but
#   set defines no __pow__, __lshift__, or __rshift__. All three in-place
#   variants are absent.
# multiprocessing is a process-based concurrency library; its types interact
#   exclusively through explicit method calls, subprocess lifecycle management,
#   and IPC — never through Python's in-place augmented assignment operators.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

